T1  - Estimation of regression coefficients with the help of characteristic functions
AU  - Van Montfort, Kees
AU  - Mooijaart, Ab
AU  - De Leeuw, Jan
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 41
IS  - 2
SP  - 267
EP  - 278
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90097-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900973
AB  - In this paper some easily applicable estimators of the regression coefficient in a simple regression model with errors in variables are derived. Usually one uses sample moments to estimate the regression coefficient. However, we use empirical characteristic functions in several points. Besides theoretical derivations a small study with generated data is discussed. This study compares our method with estimating methods which use higher-order moments.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Testing Slutsky symmetry in systems of linear demand equations
AU  - Silver, J.Lew
AU  - Ali, Mukhtar M.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 41
IS  - 2
SP  - 251
EP  - 266
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90096-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900961
AB  - Two methods are suggested for controlling the size of the F test for Slutsky symmetry in systems of linear demand equations. The F test is a multiple of the well-known Wald test (size corrected) in this context and we focus on F because of its simplicity and widespread use. The power of the F test is shown to be comparable to that of the likelihood ratio and Lagrange multiplier tests for a variety of simulated data sets. The size of the F test is such that the ratio of a percentile from the true distribution of F to the corresponding percentile from an F distribution is determined primarily by the sample size and the number of equations in the system. The nature of the data is found to be relatively unimportant, particularly in large systems. Size corrections for the F test for a wide variety of sample and system sizes are given. These should prove useful in applied work. A method of approximating the distribution of the F statistic is also presented.
ER  - 
